{
  "texts": [
    "In continuous FLPs, the placement of components is treated as a continuous variable, allowing flexibility in layout design.",
    "Components can be placed at any point in the continuous space [1].Discrete FLPs are often modelled as Quadratic Assignment Problem (QAP).",
    "The QAP deals with assigning a set of facilities to a set of locations in a way that minimises the sum of weighted distances between facility pairs [18].",
    "This combinatorial optimisation problem finds applications in fields ranging from manufacturing to telecommunications.Continuous FLPs, in turn, are modelled with various degrees of freedom: the Flexible Bay Structure (FBS) notation has been created by Tong [19].",
    "It allows the departments to be located only in parallel bays with varying widths."
  ]
}